<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Andaman & Nicobar</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">India's <em>Last Frontier</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">The Andaman and Nicobar Islands — India's remote archipelago in the Bay of Bengal — are among the most extraordinary places in the country and among the most ecologically significant territories in Asia. An arc of 572 islands, islets and rocks stretching 800 kilometres from north to south, of which only 37 are permanently inhabited, the Andaman and Nicobar Islands sit closer to Myanmar and Thailand than to the Indian mainland. The islands are covered in dense tropical rainforest of astonishing biodiversity — over 2,200 plant species, 270 bird species, saltwater crocodiles, dugongs (sea cows), leatherback sea turtles, Andaman wild pigs and dozens of endemic species found nowhere else on earth. The surrounding waters are among the most biodiverse marine ecosystems in the Indian Ocean — the coral reefs here contain over 550 species of coral and 1,200 species of fish, rivalling the Great Barrier Reef in biodiversity. The islands have a layered human history as dramatic as their natural one: for millennia, four indigenous groups — the Great Andamanese, Onge, Jarawa and Sentinelese (North Andaman) in the Andamans, and the Shompen and Nicobarese in the Nicobars — lived in complete isolation, developing cultures, languages and knowledge systems found nowhere else on earth. The British turned the islands into a penal colony in 1858 — the Cellular Jail in Port Blair, where Indian freedom fighters including Veer Savarkar were imprisoned in solitary cells, is the most emotionally charged site of India's independence movement. The 2004 Indian Ocean tsunami devastated parts of the archipelago, killing over 9,000 people and permanently altering some islands' geography. Today the Andaman and Nicobar Islands offer India's finest diving, some of Asia's best beaches, extraordinary wildlife and a history that ranges from the Stone Age to the independence movement.</p>
</section>

<section id="weather" class="fade-in">
