  {emoji:"🏛️",name:"Cellular Jail — Kala Pani",location:"Port Blair, South Andaman",desc:"The most emotionally charged monument in India's independence movement — the Cellular Jail (built 1896-1906) was where the British imprisoned Indian freedom fighters in solitary confinement, deliberately isolating each prisoner in individual cells (hence 'cellular'). Veer Savarkar, Batukeshwar Dutt and hundreds of other nationalists spent years here in conditions of extraordinary brutality. The evening Sound & Light show narrates the history with remarkable power. A mandatory pilgrimage for every Indian.",fee:["Rs.30 Indians","Rs.100 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🏖️",name:"Radhanagar Beach (Beach No. 7)",location:"Havelock Island (Swaraj Dweep)",desc:"Repeatedly voted Asia's best beach — a 2km arc of powder-white sand fringed with ancient Gurjan trees, with the clear turquoise waters of the Bay of Bengal in front. The beach faces west, making it one of India's finest sunset beaches. The water is calm, clear and inviting, with a gently shelving sandy bottom. It is set within a forest that runs down to the beach — no resorts directly on the sand, preserving its pristine quality. At its finest in the golden light of late afternoon.",fee:["Rs.50 beach conservation fee"]},
  {emoji:"🤿",name:"Havelock Island Diving & Snorkelling",location:"Havelock Island (Swaraj Dweep)",desc:"India's finest scuba diving destination — the coral reefs around Havelock offer 30+ metre visibility in peak season (Nov-Apr) with extraordinary marine biodiversity: manta rays, whale sharks, sea turtles, reef sharks, Napoleon wrasses, clownfish in anemones, nudibranchs and giant clams. Elephant Beach on the island's north has a reef accessible by snorkel just 50m from shore — one of India's best snorkelling sites. Multiple PADI-certified dive operators run courses from beginner to advanced.",fee:["Paid — dive packages"]},
  {emoji:"🌊",name:"Neil Island (Shaheed Dweep)",location:"Neil Island",desc:"A quieter, smaller and more intimate alternative to Havelock — Neil Island has three beautiful beaches (Laxmanpur, Bharatpur and Sitapur), a natural rock arch (Natural Bridge) carved by the sea, excellent snorkelling at Bharatpur and a slow island rhythm that Havelock is losing to tourism. The island is covered in farmland (it supplies most of Port Blair's vegetables) and has a small, charming village centre. The sunrise at Sitapur Beach is legendary.",fee:["Free beaches"]},
  {emoji:"🐊",name:"Crocodile Safari — Baratang Island",location:"Baratang, Middle Andaman",desc:"Baratang Island offers one of India's most dramatic natural experiences — the journey itself, through the dense Jarawa Tribal Reserve forest in a convoy of vehicles (no stopping, no photography of Jarawa people), creates a palpable sense of entering another world. At Baratang: limestone caves of extraordinary formations, India's only mud volcano (a natural geological curiosity), and mangrove creek boat safaris where saltwater crocodiles, herons and kingfishers are abundant.",fee:["Paid — ferry + cave entry"]},
  {emoji:"🏝️",name:"Ross Island (Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose Island)",location:"2km from Port Blair",desc:"The former British administrative headquarters — Ross Island, a 15-minute ferry from Port Blair, is now a hauntingly beautiful ruin where nature is reclaiming an entire colonial city. The roots of enormous Bodhi trees split through the Commissioner's house, the church, the tennis courts and the bakery. Spotted deer wander freely through the ruins. The British called it the 'Paris of the East'. It was later occupied by the Japanese in WWII. Now administered by the Indian Navy.",fee:["Rs.50 Indians","Rs.150 Foreigners"]},
  {emoji:"🌋",name:"Barren Island Volcano",location:"92km northeast of Port Blair",desc:"South Asia's only active volcano — Barren Island erupts intermittently and has been increasingly active since 1991. Boat trips from Port Blair circumnavigate the island (landing is not permitted) as lava can be seen flowing into the sea during active phases. Even during quieter periods, the volcanic island rising from the Bay of Bengal — with its sulphur clouds and blackened lava fields — is an extraordinary sight. The surrounding waters are some of the best big-fish diving in India.",fee:["Paid — boat charter"]},
  {emoji:"🐢",name:"Turtle Nesting — Galathea Bay",location:"Great Nicobar Island (restricted)",desc:"The world's largest nesting site for leatherback sea turtles (Dermochelys coriacea) — Galathea Bay on Great Nicobar Island hosts thousands of nesting leatherbacks annually, one of the most significant marine turtle nesting events on earth. Access is restricted (requires special permit and approval from the Andaman administration). The island is also home to the Shompen — one of the world's most isolated indigenous peoples — and the Nicobar megapode, an extraordinary bird.",fee:["Special restricted area permit required"]},
  {emoji:"🏊",name:"North Bay & Jolly Buoy Coral Parks",location:"South Andaman",desc:"North Bay Island offers glass-bottom boat rides over the coral gardens for non-swimmers; Jolly Buoy Island (open alternating months to allow reef recovery) is the premier snorkelling and diving site in South Andaman — pristine coral gardens with exceptional visibility. The coral restoration program here is one of India's most successful. Both islands are day-trip destinations from Port Blair, accessible by government ferries.",fee:["Paid — ferry + snorkel equipment"]},
];

const artsData=[
  {emoji:"🎨",name:"Nicobari Tribal Art & Craftsmanship",location:"Nicobar Islands (restricted)",desc:"The Nicobarese people have developed extraordinary craft traditions over millennia — intricate woven goods from pandanus and coconut palm leaves, beautifully carved wooden figures representing ancestral spirits (Kar-Nicobar figures), decorated fishing canoes and ritual objects. The Nicobarese coconut-leaf weaving produces baskets, mats and ceremonial items of remarkable precision. Most authentic Nicobarese crafts are not commercially available — they exist within living community practice."},
  {emoji:"🐚",name:"Shell Craft & Marine Art",location:"Port Blair markets",desc:"The Andamans have a distinctive shell craft tradition — the extraordinary variety of shells found in these waters (cowries, conches, nautilus, spider shells) have been crafted into jewelry, decorative objects and household items. The Port Blair local market and Aberdeen Bazaar sell shell craft alongside coral-free marine souvenirs. Note: collection of live shells, corals or marine organisms is illegal under the Wildlife Protection Act."},
